caption:
Freelance photographer Yile Yang (@kononekome) aims to capture the uncertainties of everyday life. Yile’s photos are a reflection of the emotions she encountered when she left her homeland of Beijing, China, to work in Tokyo. “I began working for this big company, only to realize how tough it was to convey thoughts and reach agreements with people who were different from me in many ways,” the 25-year-old says. She turned to her camera and found herself on a new path. “Photos don’t eliminate the things you don’t understand, and at the same time you’re not forced to define them as well,” Yile says. “What fascinates me about photography is that it shows you both the visible and invisible side of things all at once.”
Discover more stories from the Japanese community on @instagramjapan.
Photo by @kononekome

caption:
At the 2012 London Olympics, British boxer Nicola Adams (@nicolaadamsmbe) made history as the first-ever woman to win an Olympic title for boxing. “I am hoping to inspire more women to get into boxing,” the gold-medal winner, currently competing in Rio, says. “I hope I can be a role model for other females to get involved and further prove that it is possible for women to take part and succeed in the sport.” Nicola constantly breaks new ground for her sport and her country; she credits her trailblazing courage to her mother’s perseverance. “I’ve watched my mum work incredibly hard her whole life, and it inspired me that you can do anything you want — as long as you put your mind to it,” she says. “I’ve always just wanted to win. I don’t think about losing until it happens.”
Video by @nicolaadamsmbe

caption:
A year ago, Amanda (@colonlessfemale) didn’t realize that losing her colon would be one of the best things that ever happened to her. But for her, #GoingThroughIt meant understanding body positivity in a whole new light. “We’re all different ethnicities. We’re all different races. There’s not just one form of perfect — so I think I’m perfect,” 18-year-old Amanda says. “I’ve been through many things in my life, and I have scars and a poop bag. To me, healthy body image is about owning yourself and being like, ‘OK, this isn’t perfect, but I’m going to make it look cool.’ Everything is cute if you make it cute. If you’re like, ‘I look perfect in this,’ people are going to be like, ‘Oh, my god, they’re so pretty.’”
This is the first post of our new series #GoingThroughIt, which highlights young people creating amazing communities of support on Instagram. Read our extended Q&A with Amanda on our blog (link in bio) and follow her account for even more body positivity vibes.
Photo of @colonlessfemale by @veronicamreynaud
